7:14:06 AM [express] POST /api/mealplan 200 in 83778ms :: {"week_summary":"20-year-old moderately active male (170 cm, 65 kg, Vata dominant) aiming to support liver function with Indian cuisine, no allergies or restrictions, and up to 1 hour for cooking.","hydration":"Aim for about 2.5â€“3 liters of fluids daily, favoring warm water or herbal infusions; keep a 1-liter bottle at your desk and finish it by lunchtime, then refill and finish the second by early evening.","weekly_strategy":"Meals emphasize warm, lightly spiced, moist preparations to pacify Vata while using liver-supportive foods like beets, greens, turmeric, amla, lemon, papaya, and cruciferous and gourd vegetables. Each day targets ~2,400â€“2,600 kcal with adequate protein from dals, paneer, curd, and whole grains, while keeping fats moderate and focusing on digestible combinations. Spices like cumin, fennel, coriander, hing, and methi are used gently to aid agni (digestion) without aggravating Vata.","clinician_note":"","days":[{"day":1,"day_name":"Monday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Moong Dal Vegetable Chilla with Coriander Chutney","ingredients":["Split yellow moong dal (soaked)","Grated carrot","Finely chopped spinach","Coriander leaves","Ginger","Cumin seeds","Turmeric powder","Asafoetida (hing)","Rock salt","Ghee or cold-pressed sesame oil","Green chutney (coriander, mint, lemon, roasted cumin, a little curd)"],"portion":"3 medium chillas + 2 tbsp chutney (~320g)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"45g","fat":"10g","calories":"360 kcal"},"why":"Warm, lightly oiled moong chillas are easy to digest and grounding for Vata, while turmeric, coriander, and cumin support digestion and gentle liver cleansing to start the day.","substitutions":["Replace spinach with finely chopped methi (fenugreek) leaves in winter.","Use little millet or jowar flour in the batter if you prefer a grain-based version."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Papaya and Pomegranate Fruit Bowl with Fennel","ingredients":["Ripe papaya cubes","Pomegranate arils","Soaked fennel seeds (saunf)","Few drops of lemon juice"],"portion":"1 small bowl (~200g fruit)","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"32g","fat":"1g","calories":"140 kcal"},"why":"Papaya and pomegranate are tridoshic and gentle on Vata while supporting liver detox pathways; fennel aids digestion and reduces gas.","substitutions":["Swap papaya with orange segments if papaya is not available.","Use guava instead of pomegranate in season (chew well)."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Beetroot-Drumstick Sambar with Steamed Rice and Cabbage Thoran","ingredients":["Toor dal","Beetroot cubes","Drumstick pieces","Curry leaves","Onion","Tomato","Tamarind pulp (small amount)","Sambar powder","Turmeric","Mustard seeds","Hing","Ghee or sesame oil","Steamed white rice","Cabbage (shredded)","Grated coconut","Green chilli (small)","Cumin seeds"],"portion":"Sambar 1.5 cups (~300g) + rice 1.5 cups cooked (~225g) + cabbage thoran 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"20g","carbs":"80g","fat":"14g","calories":"540 kcal"},"why":"Beetroot and drumstick support liver function and provide minerals, while warm sambar with rice is grounding for Vata; cabbage cooked with coconut becomes more digestible and less gas-forming.","substitutions":["Use moong dal instead of toor dal if you want an even lighter sambar.","Replace cabbage with bottle gourd (lauki) stir-fry for a more hydrating side."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Roasted Sweet Potato Chaat with Lemon and Coriander","ingredients":["Boiled or roasted sweet potato cubes","Chopped coriander leaves","Roasted cumin powder","Black salt or rock salt","Few drops lemon juice","A drizzle of ghee"],"portion":"1 medium sweet potato (~150g cooked)","macros":{"protein":"3g","carbs":"32g","fat":"4g","calories":"190 kcal"},"why":"Sweet potato is excellent for grounding Vata and provides slow carbs, while lemon and cumin lightly stimulate the liver and digestion without being harsh.","substitutions":["Use boiled potatoes instead of sweet potato if unavailable.","Add some boiled black chana for extra protein if desired."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Khichdi with Bottle Gourd and Carrot, Served with Beet Raita","ingredients":["Split yellow moong dal","Short-grain rice","Bottle gourd (lauki) cubes","Carrot cubes","Ginger","Cumin seeds","Turmeric","Hing","Ghee","Rock salt","Plain cowâ€™s milk curd","Grated boiled beetroot","Roasted cumin powder","Coriander leaves"],"portion":"Khichdi 2 cups (~350g) + beet raita 1/2 cup (~100g)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"70g","fat":"12g","calories":"480 kcal"},"why":"Warm, soft khichdi is ideal to pacify Vata and is easy on the liver at night, while beets in raita add gentle liver support and probiotics aid digestion.","substitutions":["Replace rice with quinoa for a higher protein version.","Use pumpkin instead of bottle gourd in cooler weather."]}}},{"day":2,"day_name":"Tuesday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Vegetable Upma with Curry Leaves and Peas","ingredients":["Semolina (rava)","Onion","Carrot","Green peas","Curry leaves","Mustard seeds","Chana dal (small amount)","Ginger","Green chilli (optional, mild)","Ghee or coconut oil","Lemon wedge","Coriander leaves","Salt"],"portion":"1 medium bowl (~300g)","macros":{"protein":"10g","carbs":"55g","fat":"11g","calories":"390 kcal"},"why":"Warm, moist upma with vegetables and curry leaves pacifies Vata and provides sustained energy, while peas and curry leaves support digestion and liver enzyme activity.","substitutions":["Use broken wheat (dalia) instead of semolina for more fiber.","Replace peas with finely chopped beans if peas are not available."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Amla-Honey Warm Water Shot with Soaked Almonds","ingredients":["Amla juice or amla powder","Warm water","Honey (small amount, not heated directly)","Soaked almonds (peeled)"],"portion":"1 small glass (~150 ml) + 6 almonds (~12g)","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"8g","fat":"6g","calories":"90 kcal"},"why":"Amla is a classic Ayurvedic liver and blood tonic, and soaked almonds provide grounding fats and protein to stabilize Vata without burdening the liver.","substitutions":["Replace honey with a small piece of jaggery stirred into warm (not hot) water.","Use fresh lemon juice if amla isnâ€™t accessible."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Rajma Masala with Jeera Brown Rice and Kachumber Salad","ingredients":["Kidney beans (rajma, cooked)","Onion","Tomato","Ginger-garlic paste","Coriander powder","Cumin powder","Turmeric","Garam masala (small quantity)","Bay leaf","Coriander leaves","Ghee or mustard oil","Brown rice","Cumin seeds","Cucumber","Tomato","Carrot","Lemon juice","Salt"],"portion":"Rajma 1.25 cups (~250g) + brown rice 1.25 cups cooked (~200g) + salad 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"85g","fat":"12g","calories":"550 kcal"},"why":"Rajma offers high-quality plant protein for your age and activity, while cumin, coriander, and turmeric support digestion and liver metabolism; brown rice gives fiber but is cooked well to keep it Vata-friendly.","substitutions":["Use white rice instead of brown rice if you feel gassy or heavy.","Replace rajma with masoor dal if you want a lighter legume that day."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Masala Chaas (Spiced Buttermilk) with Roasted Chana","ingredients":["Plain curd","Water","Roasted cumin powder","Chopped coriander leaves","Grated ginger (tiny amount)","Black salt","Roasted whole chana (Bengal gram)","Fennel seeds (lightly crushed)"],"portion":"Masala chaas 1 glass (~200 ml) + roasted chana 1 small handful (~25g)","macros":{"protein":"7g","carbs":"14g","fat":"4g","calories":"120 kcal"},"why":"Chaas cools and supports the gut-liver axis with probiotics, while roasted chana offers light protein and fennel/cumin enhance digestive fire without aggravating Vata.","substitutions":["Replace roasted chana with a small piece of jaggery if you want something sweeter.","Use plant-based yogurt if you avoid dairy in future."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Phulka, Palak Moong Dal, and Stir-fried Pumpkin","ingredients":["Whole wheat flour","Water","Ghee","Split green moong dal (with skin or without, well cooked)","Spinach (palak, chopped)","Garlic (small amount)","Cumin seeds","Turmeric","Hing","Pumpkin cubes","Mustard seeds","Curry leaves","Salt"],"portion":"Phulka 3 small (~90g flour) + palak moong dal 1.5 cups (~250g) + pumpkin sabzi 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"20g","carbs":"75g","fat":"12g","calories":"510 kcal"},"why":"Moong with spinach is light yet nourishing for Vata and provides folate and minerals for liver enzymes; pumpkin sabzi adds sweetness and grounding qualities with easy digestibility.","substitutions":["Replace wheat phulkas with jowar rotis if you want more variety.","Swap pumpkin with bottle gourd for a more cooling option."]}}},{"day":3,"day_name":"Wednesday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Vegetable Poha with Peanuts and Lemon","ingredients":["Thick beaten rice (poha)","Onion","Carrot","Green peas","Curry leaves","Mustard seeds","Turmeric","Peanuts (roasted, small amount)","Green chilli (optional, mild)","Lemon wedge","Coriander leaves","Ghee or groundnut oil","Salt"],"portion":"1 large bowl (~300g)","macros":{"protein":"10g","carbs":"60g","fat":"11g","calories":"410 kcal"},"why":"Warm, moist poha prepared with ghee and vegetables is easy on Vata and gives quick energy, while turmeric and lemon gently support liver detoxification.","substitutions":["Use rolled oats instead of poha for an oats upma-style dish.","Replace peanuts with cashews if peanuts cause bloating."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Stewed Apple with Cinnamon and Raisins","ingredients":["Apple slices","Water","Raisins","Cinnamon stick","Small amount of ghee"],"portion":"1 medium apple stewed (~180g)","macros":{"protein":"1g","carbs":"27g","fat":"2g","calories":"130 kcal"},"why":"Lightly cooked apple is very Vata-friendly and supports gentle detox; cinnamon and raisins add warmth and mild sweetness supportive of liver metabolism without being heavy.","substitutions":["Use pear instead of apple if preferred.","Skip raisins if you want lower sugar content."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Masoor Dal Tadka with Jeera Rice and Beet-Carrot Poriyal","ingredients":["Red lentils (masoor dal)","Tomato","Onion","Turmeric","Cumin seeds","Mustard seeds","Garlic (optional, small)","Ghee","Coriander leaves","White rice","Cumin seeds","Beetroot (thinly sliced or grated)","Carrot (grated)","Grated coconut","Curry leaves","Salt"],"portion":"Dal 1.5 cups (~280g) + rice 1.25 cups cooked (~200g) + poriyal 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"82g","fat":"11g","calories":"530 kcal"},"why":"Masoor is one of the lighter dals, suitable for Vata when well cooked, and beets with carrots plus coconut offer antioxidants and gentle liver support in a cooked, digestible form.","substitutions":["Replace masoor with moong if you notice gas.","Use barley instead of rice occasionally for variety, cooking it very soft for Vata."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Jowar Vegetable Dhokla with Coriander Chutney","ingredients":["Jowar flour","Gram flour (besan)","Curd","Water","Grated carrot","Coriander leaves","Green chilli (very mild)","Eno or baking soda (small amount)","Mustard seeds","Sesame seeds","Curry leaves","Oil","Salt"],"portion":"4â€“5 small pieces (~120g) + 2 tbsp chutney (~30g)","macros":{"protein":"8g","carbs":"30g","fat":"6g","calories":"220 kcal"},"why":"Steamed dhokla is light and warm enough for Vata, while jowar adds whole-grain diversity and coriander in the chutney supports liver function.","substitutions":["Use only besan if jowar flour isnâ€™t available.","Replace curd with lemon juice and water for a dairy-free version."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Quinoa Khichdi with Mixed Vegetables and Coconut-Coriander Chutney","ingredients":["Quinoa","Split moong dal","Carrot","Beans","Peas","Pumpkin","Ginger","Cumin seeds","Turmeric","Hing","Ghee","Salt","Grated coconut","Coriander leaves","Green chilli (optional, mild)","Lemon juice"],"portion":"Khichdi 2 cups (~350g) + chutney 2 tbsp (~30g)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"65g","fat":"12g","calories":"470 kcal"},"why":"Quinoa plus moong provides complete protein in a soft, warm dish suitable for Vata, and the light spices and coriander-coconut chutney aid digestion and liver support without heaviness.","substitutions":["Replace quinoa with rice if quinoa feels too drying.","Use bottle gourd instead of pumpkin for a lighter variant."]}}},{"day":4,"day_name":"Thursday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Savory Oats Porridge with Vegetables and Curry Leaves","ingredients":["Rolled oats","Water and milk (or just water)","Carrot","Peas","Onion","Curry leaves","Mustard seeds","Cumin seeds","Ginger","Turmeric","Ghee","Salt"],"portion":"1 large bowl (~320g)","macros":{"protein":"12g","carbs":"50g","fat":"9g","calories":"360 kcal"},"why":"Warm, soft oats with vegetables and mild spices is excellent for Vata and provides soluble fiber that supports cholesterol and indirectly benefits liver health.","substitutions":["Use barley flakes instead of oats for variety.","Replace milk with thin coconut milk if you prefer."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Banana-Guava Bowl with Toasted Coconut","ingredients":["Ripe banana slices","Guava pieces (ripe, deseeded if hard seeds)","Fresh grated or lightly toasted coconut","Few fennel seeds (lightly crushed)"],"portion":"1 small bowl (~200g fruit)","macros":{"protein":"3g","carbs":"35g","fat":"5g","calories":"210 kcal"},"why":"Banana and coconut are grounding for Vata, while guava provides vitamin C and fiber; fennel supports digestion so the liver is not overburdened.","substitutions":["Replace guava with orange segments if not in season.","Skip coconut if you want a lighter snack."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Lauki Chana Dal Curry with Phulka and Carrot-Cucumber Raita","ingredients":["Bottle gourd (lauki) cubes","Chana dal (soaked and cooked softly)","Tomato","Onion","Ginger","Turmeric","Coriander powder","Cumin seeds","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","Whole wheat flour","Water","Curd","Grated carrot","Chopped cucumber","Roasted cumin powder","Salt"],"portion":"Lauki chana dal 1.5 cups (~280g) + 3 small phulkas (~90g flour) + raita 1/2 cup (~100g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"78g","fat":"13g","calories":"540 kcal"},"why":"Lauki is light and supports liver function while chana dal provides protein; raita cools and supports digestion, making this meal balanced and Vata-friendly if dal is well cooked.","substitutions":["Use moong dal instead of chana dal if you feel bloated.","Replace wheat phulkas with bajra rotis in winter (add a bit more ghee for Vata)."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Warm Lemon-Cumin Water with Small Handful of Nuts","ingredients":["Warm water","Fresh lemon juice","Roasted cumin powder","Pinch of rock salt","Almonds","Walnuts"],"portion":"1 glass (~200 ml) + 8â€“10 mixed nuts (~15g)","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"4g","fat":"10g","calories":"110 kcal"},"why":"Lemon-cumin water mildly stimulates bile flow and liver cleansing; a few nuts provide grounding fats and protein to keep Vata stable in the evening.","substitutions":["Replace walnuts with pistachios if preferred.","Skip nuts and add a small piece of jaggery if you want less fat."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Idli with Sambar (Drumstick and Pumpkin) and Coconut Chutney","ingredients":["Idli batter (parboiled rice and urad dal fermented)","Toor or moong dal for sambar","Drumstick pieces","Pumpkin cubes","Onion","Tomato","Sambar powder","Turmeric","Curry leaves","Mustard seeds","Hing","Oil or ghee","Grated coconut","Coriander leaves","Green chilli (mild)","Lemon or tamarind (small amount)","Salt"],"portion":"3 medium idlis (~180g) + sambar 1.5 cups (~300g) + chutney 2 tbsp (~30g)","macros":{"protein":"16g","carbs":"66g","fat":"10g","calories":"430 kcal"},"why":"Fermented idli is light and easy for Vata when eaten warm, while drumstick and pumpkin in sambar provide minerals and gentle liver support; coconut chutney adds healthy fats and satiety.","substitutions":["Use ragi idli batter for variety if you enjoy millets.","Replace pumpkin with carrots in the sambar."]}}},{"day":5,"day_name":"Friday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Besan Chilla Stuffed with Paneer and Spinach","ingredients":["Gram flour (besan)","Water","Turmeric","Cumin seeds","Salt","Ghee or oil","Paneer (crumbled)","Finely chopped spinach","Coriander leaves","Black pepper"],"portion":"2 large stuffed chillas (~320g total)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"35g","fat":"16g","calories":"430 kcal"},"why":"High-protein besan and paneer support your age and activity needs, while spinach and mild spices aid liver function; the warm, soft texture and ghee keep it Vata-pacifying.","substitutions":["Replace paneer with grated tofu if you want a lighter option.","Use methi leaves instead of spinach for a different flavour."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Orange and Pomegranate Bowl with Mint","ingredients":["Orange segments","Pomegranate arils","Few mint leaves (finely chopped)","Pinch of black salt"],"portion":"1 small bowl (~200g)","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"32g","fat":"0g","calories":"130 kcal"},"why":"Citrus and pomegranate provide vitamin C and antioxidants that support phase I and II liver detox pathways, while the small portion and mint keep it easy on Vata.","substitutions":["Replace orange with sweet lime (mosambi).","Add a few papaya cubes if you want extra sweetness."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Methi Toor Dal with Steamed Rice and Beetroot Pachadi","ingredients":["Toor dal","Fresh methi leaves (fenugreek, chopped)","Tomato","Onion","Garlic (small amount)","Turmeric","Cumin seeds","Mustard seeds","Ghee","Coriander leaves","White rice","Plain curd","Boiled grated beetroot","Green chilli (mild, optional)","Salt"],"portion":"Methi dal 1.5 cups (~280g) + rice 1.25 cups cooked (~200g) + beet pachadi 1/2 cup (~100g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"80g","fat":"12g","calories":"540 kcal"},"why":"Methi helps regulate metabolism and supports liver, while toor dal and rice give satisfying protein and carbs; beet pachadi offers additional liver-friendly antioxidants in a cooling yogurt base.","substitutions":["Use moong dal instead of toor for easier digestion.","Replace methi with spinach if methi tastes too bitter."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Spiced Vegetable Soup with Barley","ingredients":["Barley (pearled, cooked very soft)","Carrot","Pumpkin","Beans","Onion","Garlic (small amount)","Water or vegetable stock","Olive oil or ghee","Cumin powder","Black pepper","Salt","Coriander leaves"],"portion":"1 medium bowl (~250g)","macros":{"protein":"6g","carbs":"28g","fat":"4g","calories":"180 kcal"},"why":"A warm, soft soup soothes Vata and includes barley and vegetables that gently support liver and digestion without heaviness.","substitutions":["Replace barley with small quantity of rice if barley feels too rough.","Add a few peas for extra protein."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Stuffed Lauki (Bottle Gourd) Boats with Moong-Chana Filling and Lemon Rice","ingredients":["Bottle gourd (lauki, halved and scooped)","Split moong dal (cooked)","Cooked black chana or kabuli chana (small amount)","Onion","Tomato","Ginger","Cumin powder","Turmeric","Garam masala (small)","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","Cooked rice","Lemon juice","Curry leaves","Mustard seeds","Peanuts (small amount)","Salt"],"portion":"2 stuffed lauki boats (~220g) + lemon rice 1 cup (~180g)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"70g","fat":"13g","calories":"500 kcal"},"why":"Bottle gourd is hydrating and supports liver and kidneys, while the moong-chana mix gives protein; lemon rice adds tang and mild liver stimulation, with warm spices and ghee to keep it Vata-friendly.","substitutions":["Replace black/kabuli chana with only moong dal if you want it lighter.","Use quinoa instead of rice for higher protein."]}}},{"day":6,"day_name":"Saturday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Idiyappam (String Hoppers) with Vegetable Stew","ingredients":["Rice flour","Hot water","Salt","Coconut milk (thin for stew)","Carrot","Beans","Potato (small)","Onion","Ginger","Curry leaves","Black pepper (very mild)","Coconut oil"],"portion":"Idiyappam 3 nests (~150g) + vegetable stew 1.25 cups (~220g)","macros":{"protein":"7g","carbs":"65g","fat":"12g","calories":"420 kcal"},"why":"Soft rice noodles with mild coconut-based stew are soothing and grounding for Vata; gentle spices and coconut support digestive comfort and do not tax the liver when portions are moderate.","substitutions":["Use appam instead of idiyappam if preferred.","Replace potato with pumpkin for lighter stew."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Mango-Amla Smoothie (Seasonal) with Turmeric","ingredients":["Ripe mango pieces (in season, not sour)","Amla juice or powder (small amount)","Thin buttermilk or water","Pinch turmeric","Pinch black pepper","Honey or jaggery (optional, small)"],"portion":"1 glass (~200 ml)","macros":{"protein":"3g","carbs":"32g","fat":"2g","calories":"150 kcal"},"why":"Mango in moderation can pacify Vata, while amla and turmeric offer strong antioxidant and hepatoprotective support for liver function.","substitutions":["Replace mango with papaya in off-season.","Use plain water instead of buttermilk if mixing fruits and dairy feels heavy."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Chole (Chickpea Curry) with Jeera Rice and Kachumber with Beet","ingredients":["Kabuli chana (chickpeas, soaked and cooked)","Onion","Tomato","Ginger-garlic paste","Coriander powder","Cumin powder","Turmeric","Chole masala (small)","Bay leaf","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","White or brown rice","Cumin seeds","Cucumber","Tomato","Grated beetroot (small amount)","Lemon juice","Salt"],"portion":"Chole 1.25 cups (~250g) + jeera rice 1.25 cups cooked (~200g) + salad 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"21g","carbs":"85g","fat":"13g","calories":"560 kcal"},"why":"Chickpeas provide good protein and fiber, while spices like cumin and coriander aid digestion; beet in the salad adds additional liver-supporting nutrients, but good cooking and seasoning help keep it tolerable for Vata.","substitutions":["Use black chana instead of kabuli for a slightly lighter option.","Replace rice with phulkas if you prefer flatter breads that day."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Moong Sprout and Vegetable Usal (Light Cooked Sprouts)","ingredients":["Moong sprouts (lightly steamed)","Onion","Tomato","Grated carrot","Mustard seeds","Curry leaves","Turmeric","Cumin powder","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","Lemon juice","Salt"],"portion":"1 small bowl (~180g)","macros":{"protein":"9g","carbs":"24g","fat":"4g","calories":"170 kcal"},"why":"Lightly cooked sprouts are more Vata-friendly than raw, and provide enzymes and plant protein that support overall metabolism and liver health.","substitutions":["Use regular cooked moong dal instead of sprouts if you feel gassy.","Add a spoon of grated coconut for extra grounding."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Vegetable Pulao with Peas, Carrot, and Beans Served with Cucumber Raita","ingredients":["Basmati rice","Green peas","Carrot","Beans","Onion","Whole spices (bay leaf, cloves, small cinnamon)","Ghee or oil","Ginger","Coriander leaves","Salt","Curd","Grated cucumber","Roasted cumin powder","Black pepper (tiny pinch)"],"portion":"Pulao 2 cups (~320g) + raita 1/2 cup (~100g)","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"80g","fat":"14g","calories":"520 kcal"},"why":"A mildly spiced vegetable pulao provides comfort and grounding for Vata, while peas add protein; raita cools and supports digestion so the liver is not overburdened at night.","substitutions":["Use quinoa instead of rice for more protein.","Replace peas with paneer cubes if you want extra protein and richness."]}}},{"day":7,"day_name":"Sunday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Masala Vegetable Dosa with Sambar","ingredients":["Dosa batter (rice and urad dal, fermented)","Potato (boiled and mashed)","Carrot (grated)","Peas","Onion","Mustard seeds","Turmeric","Curry leaves","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","Toor or moong dal for sambar","Drumstick","Carrot","Tomato","Onion","Sambar powder","Tamarind (small amount)","Salt"],"portion":"1 large masala dosa (~200g) + sambar 1 cup (~200g)","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"70g","fat":"12g","calories":"480 kcal"},"why":"Fermented dosa batter is relatively light and good for digestion when eaten warm, and the vegetable masala plus sambar provide a range of Vata-friendly cooked veggies including drumstick for liver support.","substitutions":["Make a plain dosa without potato if you want it lighter.","Use adai (mixed dal dosa) for higher protein but add more ghee to pacify Vata."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Spiced Coconut Water with Lemon and Mint","ingredients":["Fresh coconut water","Few drops of lemon juice","Mint leaves (lightly crushed)","Pinch of roasted cumin powder"],"portion":"1 glass (~250 ml)","macros":{"protein":"1g","carbs":"11g","fat":"0g","calories":"45 kcal"},"why":"Coconut water rehydrates and cools gently while providing electrolytes, supporting liver and kidney function; cumin and mint aid digestion and suit Vata in warm weather.","substitutions":["Use plain warm water with lemon and cumin if coconut water is unavailable.","Add a small piece of jaggery if you want it slightly sweeter."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Paneer Bhurji with Soft Phulkas and Beet-Carrot Salad","ingredients":["Paneer (crumbled)","Onion","Tomato","Capsicum (small amount)","Turmeric","Coriander powder","Cumin seeds","Ginger","Ghee or oil","Coriander leaves","Whole wheat flour","Water","Grated beetroot","Grated carrot","Lemon juice","Salt","Black pepper"],"portion":"Paneer bhurji 1.25 cups (~220g) + 3 phulkas (~90g flour) + salad 1/2 cup (~80g)","macros":{"protein":"25g","carbs":"70g","fat":"20g","calories":"600 kcal"},"why":"Paneer supplies high-quality protein and healthy fats, which ground Vata and support tissue rebuilding, while beet-carrot salad (in small quantity and ideally lightly sautĂ©ed if raw feels gassy) adds liver-friendly antioxidants.","substitutions":["Replace paneer with scrambled eggs if you eat eggs.","Lightly steam the beet-carrot instead of serving raw if digestion is sensitive."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Ragi Malt with Jaggery and Cardamom","ingredients":["Ragi (finger millet) flour","Water","Milk or thin coconut milk","Jaggery","Cardamom powder","Ghee (small amount)"],"portion":"1 cup (~200 ml)","macros":{"protein":"5g","carbs":"30g","fat":"5g","calories":"190 kcal"},"why":"Warm ragi malt is grounding, calcium-rich, and good for Vata, especially in the evening, while jaggery and ghee support gentle nourishment without overloading the liver when used moderately.","substitutions":["Use barley flour instead of ragi for a different grain.","Replace jaggery with a small amount of dates if desired."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Vegetable Handi Biryani with Curd","ingredients":["Basmati rice (parboiled partially)","Mixed vegetables (carrot, beans, peas, cauliflower in small quantity, potato)","Onion","Tomato","Ginger-garlic paste (small amount)","Whole spices (bay leaf, cloves, cardamom, small cinnamon)","Turmeric","Coriander powder","Garam masala (small)","Ghee or oil","Mint leaves","Coriander leaves","Milk or water for dum","Plain curd","Roasted cumin powder","Salt"],"portion":"Biryani 2 cups (~320g) + curd 1/2 cup (~100g)","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"80g","fat":"16g","calories":"540 kcal"},"why":"A mildly spiced, ghee-enriched biryani in moderate portion is grounding and satisfying for Vata, and pairing it with plain curd supports digestion so the meal is not too heavy for the liver at night.","substitutions":["Use brown rice but cook very soft if you want more fiber.","Replace part of the rice with soaked moong to raise protein and lighten the dish."]}}}]}
